          "content": "Here's how to test the WebSocket server and client yourself:\n\n## **Step-by-Step Testing Guide**\n\n### **1. Open Two Terminals**\n\n**Terminal 1 - Start Server:**\n```bash\ncd /mnt/d/coding/projects/NXP\n./build/examples/websocket_server\n```\n\n**Terminal 2 - Start Client:**\n```bash\ncd /mnt/d/coding/projects/NXP\n./build/examples/websocket_client 127.0.0.1\n```\n\n### **2. What You Should See**\n\n**Server Terminal:**\n- ✅ Server listening on 0.0.0.0:8080\n- 📥 Received packets from client\n- 💬 Chat stream messages\n- 🔔 Notification stream messages\n- 📊 Data stream messages\n- 📤 Sent packets to client\n\n**Client Terminal:**\n- ✅ Connected to server\n- 💬 Sending chat messages\n- 🔔 Sending notifications\n- 📊 Sending data\n- 📥 Receiving server responses\n\n### **3. What's Being Tested**\n\n✅ **Multiple Streams** - 3 independent streams per connection:\n- Chat stream (bidirectional messages)\n- Notification stream (server → client updates)\n- Data stream (JSON-like structured data)\n\n✅ **No Head-of-Line Blocking** - Each stream is independent\n\n✅ **Real Network** - Actual UDP packets over localhost\n\n✅ **Connection Stats** - Bytes sent/received, packet counts\n\n### **4. Quick Test Commands**\n\n```bash\n# Test 1: Run server only (check if it binds to port)\n./build/examples/websocket_server\n\n# Test 2: In another terminal, run client\n./build/examples/websocket_client 127.0.0.1\n\n# Test 3: Check if port is listening\nnetstat -tulpn | grep 8080\n\n# Test 4: Monitor packets (optional)\nsudo tcpdump -i lo port 8080 -X\n```\n\n### **5. Expected Behavior**\n\n- Client sends 5 rounds of messages (15 total across 3 streams)\n- Server echoes chat messages back\n- Server sends periodic notifications\n- Both show statistics at the end\n- Clean shutdown with Ctrl+C\n\n### **6. Troubleshooting**\n\n**If server won't start:**\n```bash\n# Check if port is already in use\nsudo lsof -i :8080\n# Kill any process using it\nsudo kill -9 <PID>\n```\n\n**If 