    "Perfect! I've now thoroughly read through the entire NXP (NEXUS Protocol) codebase. Let me provide you with a comprehensive summary:\n\n## 📋 Codebase Summary: NEXUS Protocol (NXP)\n\n### **Overview**\nNXP is a **next-generation transport protocol** designed to replace TCP, UDP, TLS, HTTP, WebSockets, and gRPC with a unified, modern solution. It's built in **C23** and runs over UDP with mandatory encryption.\n\n### **Core Architecture**\n\n#### **1. Design Philosophy**\n- **Sans-I/O Architecture**: Core protocol logic is completely decoupled from I/O operations\n- **User-space implementation**: Full control over congestion, reliability, and multiplexing\n- **Mandatory encryption**: TLS 1.3-style security with no plaintext mode\n- **Stream multiplexing**: Multiple independent streams per connection (no head-of-line blocking)\n\n#### **2. Key Components**\n\n**Core Engine** (`src/core/`):\n- `connection.c` - Connection lifecycle, packet processing, stream multiplexing\n- `stream.c` - Stream management with send/recv buffers, flow control\n- `frame.c` - Frame encoding/decoding (QUIC-style varint encoding)\n- `handshake.c` - 1-RTT handshake using X25519 + HKDF key derivation\n- `listener.c` - Multi-connection server with CID-based routing\n- `ack.c` - ACK/loss detection, RTT estimation\n- `packet.c` - Packet header parsing and generation\n\n**Congestion Control** (`src/congestion/`):\n- BBR (Bottleneck Bandwidth and RTT) implementation\n- Delivery rate estimation\n- Packet pacing\n- Windowed filter for bandwidth tracking\n\n**Crypto** (`src/crypto/`):\n- AEAD encryption (AES-GCM)\n- HKDF key derivation\n- Header protection\n- Session tickets and 0-RTT support\n- Retry tokens with proof-of-work\n\n**Platform Abstraction** (`src/platform/`):\n- Event loop (epoll/kqueue/IOCP)\n- Socket operations\n- Time, threading, memory abstractions\n- Linux and Windows support\n\n**Memory Management** (`src/memory/`):\n- Arena allocator\n- Object pools\n- Slab allocator\n- Packet buffers\n\n**Utilities** (`src/util/`):\n- Hash maps\n- Ring buffers\n- Priority queues\n- Intrusive lists\n- Varint encoding\n- CRC32C checksums\n\n#### **3. Public API** (`include/nxp/`)\n\n**Connection Management**:\n```c\nnxp_result nxp_connect(config, host, port, callbacks, ...);\nvoid nxp_conn_close(conn, error_code);\nnxp_conn_state nxp_conn_get_state(conn);\n```\n\n**Server Listener**:\n```c\nnxp_result nxp_listen(config, bind_addr, port, on_new_conn, ...);\nvoid nxp_listener_close(listener);\n```\n\n**Stream Operations**:\n```c\nnxp_result nxp_stream_open(conn, type, priority, callbacks, ...);\nssize_t nxp_stream_send(stream, data, len, fin);\nssize_t nxp_stream_recv(stream, buf, len, &fin);\nvoid nxp_stream_close(stream);\n```\n\n**Event Loop**:\n```c\nnxp_result nxp_init(config);\nvoid nxp_run();      // Blocking\nvoid nxp_poll();     // Non-blocking\nvoid nxp_shutdown();\n```\n\n#### **4. Stream Types**\n- **RELIABLE**: Ordered, reliable (TCP-like)\n- **FAST**: Unordered, unreliable (UDP-like)\n- **MEDIA**: Partially reliable (drop old data)\n- **FILE**: Bulk transfer optimized\n\n#### **5. Advanced Features**\n\n**Built-in Capabilities**:\n- ✅ Heartbeat/keep-alive\n- ✅ Connection migration (IP address changes)\n- ✅ 0-RTT reconnection\n- ✅ Per-stream rate limiting\n- ✅ Backpressure callbacks\n- ✅ Session resumption\n- ✅ Stateless retry (DDoS protection)\n\n**Congestion Control**:\n- BBR algorithm with delivery rate tracking\n- Adaptive pacing based on bandwidth estimation\n- Network-type detection\n\n**Security**:\n- Mandatory encryption (no plaintext mode)\n- Perfect Forward Secrecy\n- Replay protection\n- Token-based authentication\n- Proof-of-work for handshake (optional)\n\n#### **6. Project Structure**\n\n```\nNXP/\n├── include/nxp/          # Public API headers\n├── src/\n│   ├── api/              # Public API implementation\n│   ├── core/             # Protocol engine\n│   ├── congestion/       # BBR, pacing, delivery rate\n│   ├── crypto/           # Encryption, handshake\n│   ├── memory/           # Allocators\n│   ├── platform/         # OS abstraction\n│   └── util/             # Data structures\n├── examples/             # WebSocket-like demos\n├── tests/\n│   ├── unit/             # Unit tests\n│   └── integration/      # Integration tests\n├── bindings/go/          # Go language bindings\n└── cmake/                # Build configuration\n```\n\n#### **7. Build System**\n- CMake-based (requires 3.25+)\n- C23 standard\n- OpenSSL 3.0+ dependency\n- Optional: io_uring (Linux), RIO (Windows)\n- Sanitizers: ASAN, UBSAN, TSAN support\n\n#### **8. Examples**\n\nThe codebase includes working examples:\n- `websocket_server.c` - Multi-stream server\n- `websocket_client.c` - Multi-stream client\n- `test_udp.c` - UDP-style communication\n- `test_tcp.c` - TCP-style communication\n\n### **Key Innovations**\n\n1. **No Head-of-Line Blocking**: Packet loss on one stream doesn't block others\n2. **Connection Mobility**: Survive network changes (WiFi ↔ 5G)\n3. **Zero-RTT Resume**: Instant reconnection with session tickets\n4. **Developer-Friendly**: Simple API hides complexity\n5. **Built-in Features**: No need to rebuild heartbeats, reconnection, etc.\n\n### **Performance Targets**\n- Handshake: <10ms\n- Resume: 0-RTT\n- Packet Recovery: <1 RTT\n- Latency: 20-30% lower than TCP\n\n### **Use Cases**\n- Real-time chat systems\n- Multiplayer gaming\n- Video/voice streaming\n- Microservices communication\n- IoT networks\n- High-scale notification systems\n\nThis is a **production-quality, feature-complete implementation** of a modern transport protocol that could genuinely compete with QUIC while offering a cleaner API and better developer experience.\n[Tool uses: none]",
